\begin_layout Subsection
Superposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is known that for simultaneous eigenstates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{i}$
\end_inset

, multiplicativity must hold.
 Consequently, any violation of multiplicativity must arise from states
 that are superpositions (of the simultaneous eigenkets).
 Note however, that entanglement is not necessary to show a violation, since
 the PM test is a state independent test, where a separable state can be
 used to arrive at a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Non Locality and Entanglement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is known from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Bell's-Theorem"

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{B}\right\rangle \le2$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 is the Bell operator as defined there.
 If we assume (1), (2) and (3), as given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Peres-Mermin-Revisited"

\end_inset

, then also it can be proven that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{B}\right\rangle \le2$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{1}=\hat{a}_{1}\otimes\hat{\mathbb{I}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{2}=\hat{\mathbb{I}}\otimes\hat{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\hat{B}_{1},\hat{B}_{2}]=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}\equiv\hat{B}_{1}\hat{B}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 From multiplicativity, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}(\hat{C})=m_{1}(\hat{B}_{1})m_{1}(\hat{B}_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 This entails that 
\begin_inset Formula $m(\hat{a}_{1}\otimes\hat{b}_{1})=m(\hat{a}_{1}\otimes\hat{\mathbb{I}})m(\hat{\mathbb{I}}\otimes\hat{b}_{1})$
\end_inset

, where the subscript has been suppressed for brevity.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $m(\hat{*})$
\end_inset

, will depend on the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and the hidden variables.
 Therefore, averaging multiple measurements, corresponds to averaging over
 the hidden variables.
 This is expressed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle m(\hat{a}_{1}\otimes\hat{b}_{1})\right\rangle =\left\langle m(\hat{a}_{1}\otimes\hat{\mathbb{I}})\right\rangle \left\langle m(\hat{\mathbb{I}}\otimes\hat{b}_{1})\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 One can repeat this argument for each term in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{B}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $-1\le m(\hat{*})\le1$
\end_inset

, and that the extrema will occur only at the extreme values of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, one can plugin 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle m(\hat{*})\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{B}\right\rangle \le2$
\end_inset

.
 We can therefore conclude that a violation of Bell's inequality, entails
 that atleast one of the three assumptions is wrong.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can infact try to show how a consistent (with QM) non-multiplicative
 theory, must be non-local.
 Formally it is clear, since a violation of Bell's inequality implies non-locali
ty.
 Consequently, any consistent completion of QM, will be non-local.
 More insight can be gained, although some care is needed.
 The notion of compatible observables is that commuting observables don't
 disturb each other and can be simultaneously known.
 While the statement is not precisely stated, we only need to note that
 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{k_{1}}(\hat{C})=m_{k_{2}}(\hat{B}_{1})m_{k_{3}}(\hat{B}_{2})$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $(k_{1},k_{2},k_{3})\in\{(1,2,3),(2,1,3),\dots\}$
\end_inset

.
 In words, this means that to measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}$
\end_inset

, one can instead first measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and then measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 A multiplication of the values obtained, can be taken to be the value a
 measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}$
\end_inset

 yields.
 This can be verified by measuring 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}$
\end_inset

 subsequently.
 The Bell scenario offers an interesting freedom, by restricting the form
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 To evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{B}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, one is required to evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{B}_{1}\hat{B}_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 From the compatibility argument, we need to find the average value of 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{3}(\hat{B}_{1}\hat{B}_{2})=m_{1}(\hat{B}_{1})m_{2}(\hat{B}_{2})$
\end_inset

, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle m_{3}(\hat{a}_{1}\otimes\hat{b}_{1})\right\rangle =\left\langle m_{1}(\hat{a}_{1}\otimes\hat{\mathbb{I}})\right\rangle \left\langle m_{2}(\hat{\mathbb{I}}\otimes\hat{b}_{1})\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 So far, the statements were general.
 Now we assume that our theory is non-multiplicative (and non-contextual).
 A consistent theory (with QM), using these assumptions, can and must violate
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{B}\right\rangle \le2$
\end_inset

.
 However, if the particles are taken far away, then the only way the theory
 can be non-multiplicative (
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}(\hat{B}_{1})\neq m_{2}(\hat{B}_{1})$
\end_inset

 for example), is if the theory is non-local.
 Locality will entail that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}(\hat{B}_{1})=m_{2}(\hat{B}_{1})$
\end_inset

 for instance, since the information about which observable was measured
 first, can't be propagated instantaneously.
 We see therefore that non-locality arises quite naturally in consistent
 non-multiplicative theories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a remark, it maybe added that in case of the Bell Test, entanglement
 is needed to show one of the three assumptions is wrong.
 This is so because it can be shown that entanglement is necessary to arrive
 at a violation of the inequality.
\end_layout

