\begin_layout Subsection
Cryptography using contextuality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Interesting collaborative progress was made in developing certain cryptography
 protocols using contextuality, with Jaskaran and Kishor, who primarily
 constructed the schemes.
 A well known idea is to use entanglement to facilitate secure sharing of
 keys, where the security assurance comes from the monogomy of Bell's inequality
 violations.
 An analogue of this idea was used, where the contextuality inequalities
 are used in place of Bell's and it was found that the said method is encouragin
gly secure and less resource hungry.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Attempt at superluminal communication with BM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imagine there are two particles, one with person A, and the other with person
 B.
 Now both measure the position of their particles.
 Thus the positions are precisely known.
 Next, they allow their particles to evolve under a Hamiltonian (interaction)
 such that they become entangled.
 Suppose at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, the particles are entangled.
 Now from the de-Broglie theory, both can predict the locations of their
 particles at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Now comes the interesting part.
 The protocol they follow, is as follows.
 Say A uses this setup, only to receive signals.
 If B wants to send a signal to A, all that he needs to do, is to disturb
 his particle at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 This would cause some change in, either the wavefunction or the position,
 or both, of the particle, compared to if B had not caused any disturbance.
 Now A measures her particle's position at 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\epsilon$
\end_inset

 and gets the value 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 She knows what position her particle should've been at, if B didn't do
 anything, call this position 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{A}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

.
 If now 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{A}\neq q_{A}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

, then she knows B sent a signal.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{A}=q_{A}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

, then she knows nothing was sent.
 Since the equations are non-local, this interaction is instantaneous, and
 in principle faster than speed of light.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Ofcourse, one can fill in the details, which is what I almost started doing,
 but finding the fault in the argument is what was pivotal.
 It turns out, the fault was rather straight forward, although a little
 subtle.
 The idea is that regardless of how precise the position measurement is,
 its uncertainty will spread with the wavefunction, thereby rendering any
 prediction useless.
 Thus, in this light, chaos restores locality.
 This is actually not too hard to see.
 Imagine you have an uncertainty 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta q$
\end_inset

, when you measured the position and got the value 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 Now we can imagine a gaussian associated with this, as the wavefunction,
 after collapse.
 Since the de-Broglie Bohm theory ensures that the probability distribution
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 is preserved by the dynamics of the particles, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 evolves, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta q$
\end_inset

 will increase (in case of free evolution), effectively destroying `position
 information'.
 The idea can only be harnessed, if one can somehow decouple the uncertainty
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 from the wavefunction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Identical Particles, an alternate approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One difficulty faced when we construct a statistical description of classical
 particles, is the Gibbs Paradox.
 At its heart, is the idea that one can always distinguish particles, on
 the basis of their paths.
 In QM, identical particles are handled quite elegantly, by (anti-)symmetrizatio
n of the wavefunction.
 In BM however, the trajectories are again well known and one might imagine
 that this signals failure of BM.
 It so turns out, that upon appropriately constructing the trajectory space,
 invariant under permutations of particles, one is able to stay consistent
 with QM and infact, able to gain further insights.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We realized however, that since QM describes reality, only through a combination
 of operators and the state, and that one can take the view that it is the
 observer that is incapable of distinguishing which particle is being looked
 at, therefore one can imagine that (anti-)symmetrizing operators should
 yield effectively the same results as (anti-)symmetrizing the wavefunctions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an illustration, consider the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle =\left|01\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 If this state represented bosons, then we'd have to write according to
 the usual methods of QM, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\left|\psi_{\text{I}}\right\rangle =\left|01\right\rangle +\left|10\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Now if we measure say 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{z}\otimes\hat{\mathbb{I}}$
\end_inset

, on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, we'd obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

, while the same measurement on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi_{\text{I}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 would yield 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 (on an average, in this case).
 However, if we instead symmetrize the operator as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\sigma_{z}\otimes\mathbb{I}+\mathbb{I}\otimes\sigma_{z}\right)/2$
\end_inset

, then even if we measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, then on average.
 We'd get 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 upon measuring 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi_{\text{I }}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 also, as is expected.
\end_layout

